Flight Delay Analysis and Prediction¶

Business Understanding¶

Flight delay analysis and prediction involves analyzing data related to flight delays and using it to predict future delays. This data can include historical flight data, weather data, airport information, and other data points. By analyzing this data, one can uncover patterns that can be used to better anticipate when a flight will be delayed, as well as understand the reasons why a flight might be delayed. This information can then be used to better plan and manage resources to minimize delays. Additionally, this analysis can be used to inform passengers of potential delays before they book a flight, so they can make more informed decisions.

Problem Description¶

Air travel is becoming increasing complex with multiple variables impacting the same. The flight delay is one of such variables impacts carrier, Airport and passenger and may result in significant commercial loss or reputation loss to all the stakeholders and thus huge cost on the economy. Thus, prediction of delay is crucial not only from view point of customer from time management perspective and carrier for retention of customer faith but also from Airport point of view for managing the traffic more efficiently to optimise the number of arriving flights by appropriate adjustment of schedules. The contribution of weather conditions has been identified to be the very important contributor of these delays. It is of the utmost interest of one of the participants of ecosystem to predict flight delays based on the flights details and predicted weather conditions by a good predictive model, which you are going to build, to take the necessary corrective and preventive actions to improve business as well as service.
The historical data containing scheduled departure and arrival times, date, origin, destination and also weather data is available and the data scientists can predict if delay can happen or not using the flight data and aviation weather data for a specific flight.

About Data:

Every single flight is observed as per their scheduled departure and arrival timestamps, to record the details of trips made, traffic conditions, etc. Flight details like Origin, destination, date of flight, scheduled departure and scheduled arrival time stamps etc.

Weather stations data details like station id along with it’s linked AirportID, ground height etc. Hourly aviation weather conditions data also provided for 2 years etc. Origin, Destination details in flight data can be mapped to the AirportID in other datasets.

Objectives:

I. Derive the Categorical Target Attribute “FlightDelayStatus”:
    1. You are expected to derive the categorical Target attribute  “FlightDelayStatus” for Train.csv as cited below

II. Predict the flight delay  ‘1’  or  ‘2’    for test set :
    2. You are expected to create an analytical and modelling framework to predict the flight delay  of each id   categorizing into “1”  or  ”2”
                    “1” indicates :  “Yes”  and
                     “2” indicates  : ”No”

Directions to derive the Target attribute for Train.csv : 1. if the delay is more than 15 minutes then FlightDelayStatus will be “1” else “2”

  • Difference https://stackoverflow.com/questions/70997939/time-difference-in-pandas-columns
  • To calculate the difference between dates is not possible in the datetime format hence we should convert it to timedelta format so that it will be very convenient to get the delay status.

This code is used to calculate the flight delay status of a given dataframe. It first converts the scheduled arrival time and the actual arrival time columns to a timedelta format. Then it calculates the difference between the two times and assigns it to a new column called Flight_Delay_status. Finally, it converts the timedelta to seconds and divides by 60 to get an output in minutes.

In [6]:
df['Sheduled_Arr_Time'] = pd.to_timedelta(df['Scheduled_Arr_Time'].astype(str))
df['ActualArrivalTime'] = pd.to_timedelta(df['ActualArrivalTime'].astype(str))
df['Flight_Delay_status'] = df['Sheduled_Arr_Time'] - df['ActualArrivalTime']

df['Flight_Delay_status'] = (df['Flight_Delay_status'] + pd.Timedelta(days=1) 
            * (df['Flight_Delay_status'] < pd.Timedelta(days=0))).dt.total_seconds() / 60

  • It is important to convert an int column to str before combining the two columns because data types must be consistent when combining two columns. If one column is a string and the other is an integer, combining them will result in an error. Converting the int column to str ensures that both columns are of the same data type and can be combined without any issues.

This code is used to calculate the flight delay status of a given dataframe. It first converts the scheduled arrival time and the actual arrival time columns to a timedelta format. Then it calculates the difference between the two times and assigns it to a new column called Flight_Delay_status. Finally, it converts the timedelta to seconds and divides by 60 to get an output in minutes.``

It is important to convert an int column to str before combining the two columns because data types must be consistent when combining two columns. If one column is a string and the other is an integer, combining them will result in an error. Converting the int column to str ensures that both columns are of the same data type and can be combined without any issues.

Final Train Data sets¶

  • This code uses the Pandas merge_asof() method to merge the two dataframes,
  • df_merged_Allstations_and_train and All_2004_hourly, on the ScheduledArrTime and Time columns respectively.
  • The merge is done by the Date and WeatherStationID columns and allows for a tolerance of 600 minutes.
  • The direction argument is set to 'nearest' to ensure that the nearest value is used when the exact value is not found.
In [104]:
# final train data after merging all the data sets
final_train = pd.merge_asof(df_merged_Allstations_and_train,df_merged_All_2004_hourly_hpd,left_on='ScheduledArrTime',right_on='Time',by=['Date','WeatherStationID'],tolerance=pd.Timedelta('600m'),direction='nearest')

A for loop is a type of loop that is used to iterate over a sequence of elements. In the above code, the for loop is used to iterate over the list of indexes of the rows with missing time values, and for each index in the list, the code replaces the missing value with the timestamp of the previous valid row.

In [121]:
# Get the index of the rows with missing time values
index_list = final_train[final_train['Time'].isnull()].index

# Iterate over the index list and replace the missing value with the timestamp of the previous valid row
for idx in index_list:
    final_train.loc[idx, 'Time'] = final_train.loc[idx-1, 'Time']

Final Test data sets

  • This code uses the Pandas merge_asof() method to merge the two dataframes,
  • df_merged_Allstations_and_train and All_2004_hourly, on the ScheduledArrTime and Time columns respectively.
  • The merge is done by the Date and WeatherStationID columns and allows for a tolerance of 600 minutes.
  • The direction argument is set to 'nearest' to ensure that the nearest value is used when the exact value is not found.
